101.7	Aspirin	Aspirin	Aspirin , also known as acetylsalicylic acid ( -əl--i--ik; abbreviated ASA), is a salicylate drug, often used as an analgesic to relieve minor aches and pains, as an antipyretic to reduce fever, and as an anti-inflammatory medication. It was first isolated by Felix Hoffmann, a chemist with the German company Bayer, under the direction of Arthur Eichengrün.	http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/67/Aspirin-skeletal.svg/150px-Aspirin-skeletal.svg.png
